\begin_layout Standard
Despite the numerous implementations, the keys determining the energetic
 accuracy of the hybrid methods of RISM with QM calculation are not thoroughly
 discussed.
 On one hand, it is well known that the solvation free energy calculated
 from 3D RISM overestimates the energy of forming cavity for solute, which
 is problematic especially for neutral ones, since their solvation free
 energy values are around several kcal/mol.
 The possible correction strategies include the repulsive bridge correction
 (RBC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kovalenko00a,book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

 term, cavity formation energy correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Truchon14"

\end_inset

 term and polar molar volume (PMV) correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Palmer10,Sergiievskyi14"

\end_inset

 term.
 On the other hand, in SCF RISM-QM calculations, the energy of solute electronic
 structure relaxation upon the solvation of the solute from gas phase to
 aqueous phase must be considered, since it is reported that the change
 in the solvation energy due to the polarization is nearly proportional
 to this term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato13,Sato07a"

\end_inset

.
