\begin_layout Standard
The detailed aspects of 3D RISM theory have been thoroughly discussed in
 previous work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Sato13,Kovalenko99a,Kovalenko00b,book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 thus here we shortly go through the fundamental formulas in the theory.
 The solute-solvent 3D RISM integral equation has the following convolution
 form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h^{uv}=c^{uv}\ast\chi^{v}.\label{eq:rism-uv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{uv}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{uv}$
\end_inset

 are (rectangular) matrices of the 3D total correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 and 3D direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

, both unknowns of the equation.
 The superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 label the solute and the solvent, respectively.
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 enumerate the solvent site interacting with the whole solute.
 In Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

, the solvent is represented by its (square symmetric) susceptibility matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{v}=\omega^{v}+\rho h^{vv}$
\end_inset

 and could be obtained self-consistently from the pure solvent 1D RISM equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "book:Hirata03,Kovalenko99b"

\end_inset

.
 In practice one operates with the dimensionless Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}^{v}(k)$
\end_inset

 of the solvent susceptibility.
 The low 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}_{\alpha\gamma}^{v}(0)=\rho\kappa/\beta$
\end_inset

 encodes the solvent compressibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and the next leading 
\begin_inset Formula $o(k^{2})$
\end_inset

 terms corrected by DRISM control the dielectric response of the solvent
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perkyns92"

\end_inset

.
 As usual 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/T$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to 1D RISM case, the closure relation is needed to render the Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

