 In this paper, the Kovalenko and Hirata (KH) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

 closure is used, which reads 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}=f(-\beta u_{\alpha}+h_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\exp(x)-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 is the interaction potential between solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the solute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the excess chemical potential of solvation could be analytically
 derived from distribution functions.
 For HNC closure, it has the following form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Singer85"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu=\frac{\rho}{\beta}\int\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N_{\text{v}}}\left[|h_{\alpha}|^{2}/2-c_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}h_{\alpha}/2\right]d^{3}r\label{eq:mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and in the corresponding expression for the KH closure the 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}$
\end_inset

-terms contribute only in the depletion regions where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}<0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

.
 This expression, together with a linear convolution relation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

, between the total and direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 leads to seriously overestimated cavity formation energies.
 Indeed, by assuming a simple liquid exposed to a potential sufficiently
 repulsive within an extended volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 and approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $h\approx-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\approx-z^{-1}$
\end_inset

