\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A series of approximations and a self-consistent hybrid approach combining
 QM solute description with 3D RISM for solvent medium reveals that for
 neutral solutes, the accuracy of calculated solvation free energies is
 mainly determined by the asymptotic error of cavity formation energies.
 Significantly better agreement with experimental results could be obtained
 by applying partial molar volume correction as also reported in previous
 non-hybrid studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Palmer10,Sergiievskyi14,Misin15"

\end_inset

.
 The undeniably useful partial molar volume correction has been previously
 justified empirically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Palmer10"

\end_inset

 and by thermodynamic arguments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sergiievskyi14"

\end_inset

 which were later disputed, however 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Song15"

\end_inset

; also a recent work advocates a different choice of the prefactor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Misin15"

\end_inset

.
 We presented an asymptotic analysis that offers an alternative interpretation
 of the error origin and leads, in case of simple liquids, to the same prefactor
 as in Ref.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Misin15"

\end_inset

 without relying on thermodynamic ensemble arguments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a comparison of approximate methods we found that two representations
 of the solute charge density, by point charges of a force-field and by
 gas-phase QM density, lead to quite comparable solvation energies with
 mean absolute deviation of about 1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol from each other and 1.4--1.6
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol from experiment.
